---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import BitField from '@/components/react/BitField.tsx';
import SubframeBuilder from '@/components/react/SubframeBuilder.tsx';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
import { E1B_PAGE, OSNMA_FIELD } from '@/data/fields';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="OSNMA on the signal"
  description="Where OSNMA lives in the Galileo E1-B I/NAV message: the 40-bit field, HKROOT and MACK."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="2 · OSNMA on the signal"
    title="Where OSNMA lives on the signal"
    lead="OSNMA is not a separate broadcast. It rides in a dedicated 40-bit field of the Galileo E1-B navigation page, assembled into two streams over each 30-second subframe."
  />

  <p>
    Galileo's Open Service data signal, <strong>E1-B</strong>, carries the I/NAV
    message as a sequence of pages. A nominal page is 120 bits, and one of its
    fields — 40 bits wide — is reserved for OSNMA <DocRef doc="icd" section="2" />.
    Select fields to see the page layout:
  </p>

  <BitField spec={E1B_PAGE} client:visible />

  <h2>Two streams in 40 bits</h2>
  <p>
    The 40-bit OSNMA field splits into a slow stream and a fast stream. The slow
    <strong>HKROOT</strong> (8 bits) carries the headers and the digitally signed
    key material; the fast <strong>MACK</strong> (32 bits) carries the tags and the
    disclosed TESLA key.
  </p>

  <BitField spec={OSNMA_FIELD} client:visible />

  <h2>Building a subframe</h2>
  <p>
    A subframe is 15 pages transmitted over 30 seconds. Each page adds its 8 + 32
    bits, so across the subframe the streams accumulate into a
    <strong>120-bit HKROOT message</strong> and a <strong>480-bit MACK message</strong>.
    Play the assembly:
  </p>

  <SubframeBuilder client:visible />

  <Callout type="note">
    <p>
      The 120-bit HKROOT holds the NMA Header (byte 1), the DSM Header (byte 2) and
      then DSM-KROOT or DSM-PKR block bits. Because a full DSM spans many subframes,
      the receiver collects HKROOT blocks over minutes and reassembles them — see
      <a href="/structures/dsm-kroot">DSM-KROOT</a> and
      <a href="/structures/dsm-pkr">DSM-PKR</a>.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <Callout type="tip">
    <p>
      Only a subset of satellites transmits OSNMA at any moment, and which ones can
      change. A receiver does not need a specific satellite: the TESLA chain and DSM
      content are common to the whole constellation, so blocks and keys can be
      gathered from whichever OSNMA satellites are in view.
    </p>
  </Callout>
</BaseLayout>
